# YouTube-to-Text Foundation

## Product goals
- Build SEO-first pages for transcript reading.
- Allow everyone to read content; only authenticated users can create processing jobs.
- Ship in small, releasable phases (incremental versions).

## Core tech stack
- Web: Next.js (App Router) + React 19 + TypeScript + Tailwind CSS.
- Auth and DB: Supabase (Auth + Postgres).
- Transcript files: store Markdown in S3-compatible storage; keep only URL + metadata in DB.
- Long-running processing: separate worker service with queue (Redis + BullMQ).
- Observability: basic error and queue monitoring (e.g., Sentry).

## Architecture constraints
- Keep content pages compatible with SSG/ISR for SEO and low serving cost.
- Do not put heavy transcript/translation logic in request-response web handlers.
- Use idempotent jobs with retry/backoff for pipeline stability.
- Keep Markdown rendering pipeline deterministic and safe.

## Implementation style
- Apply YAGNI: avoid features not needed for current phase.
- Prefer small PRs and release-ready increments.
- Keep code comments in English.

## Code documentation
- Every exported function must have a JSDoc comment in English.
- The comment must explain: what the function does, where it is used, and why it exists.
- Format: `/** ... */` above the function declaration.
- Keep comments concise (1–3 lines). Do not restate the function signature.
